{"title_page": "Thorsen House", "text_new": "{{Infobox NRHP | name =William R. Thorsen House\n  | nrhp_type = \n  | image = Thorsen House.jpg\n  | caption = \n  | location= 2307 [[Piedmont Avenue (Berkeley)|Piedmont Ave]], [[Berkeley, California]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|37|52|8.34|N|122|15|7.09|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = United States Oakland#California#USA\n  | built =1909\n  | designated_other1 = Berkeley Landmark \n  | designated_other1_date = December 15, 1975 <ref name=\"Berkeley Landmarks\">{{cite web|url=http://berkeleyheritage.com/berkeley_landmarks/landmarks1-100.html|title=Berkeley Landmarks::Landmarks #1-100|date=2010-06-06|work=Berkeley Landmarks|publisher=Berkeley Architectural Heritage Association}}</ref>\n  | designated_other1_number = 4\n  | architect= [[Greene and Greene|Greene & Greene]]<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.californiasigmaphi.org/about/thorsenhouse/|title=   The Thorsen House  \n|publisher= California Sigma Phi Society |accessdate= April 20, 2016}}</ref>\n  | architecture= [[Ultimate bungalow]], [[American Craftsman|American Arts and Crafts Movement]]\n  | added = November 20, 1978<ref name=\"nris\" />\n  | area = {{convert|0.4|acre}}\n  | governing_body = <!--Local-->Private \n  | refnum = 78000646<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''William R. Thorsen House''', often referred to as the '''Thorsen House''', is a historic residence in [[Berkeley, California]]. Built in 1909 for William and Caroline Thorsen, it is one of the last of four standing [[ultimate bungalow]]s designed by Henry and Charles Greene of the renowned architectural firm [[Greene & Greene]] and the only one located in [[Northern California]].<ref name=\":0\">{{ Thorsen|pub=isher=  California Death Index, 1940-1997 {{!}}accessd|te= A=<nowiki>ril 20, 2016}}</nowiki></ref><ref>|{{cite web={{!}}url=  https://familysearch.org/ark:|61903/1:1:=PZB-BJ4 {{!}}title }}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{field Tho|sen=publisher =  California Death Index, 1940-1997 \n|ac|essdat=<nowiki>= April 20, 2016}}</nowiki></ref>\n\nSince 1942, it has been home to the [[Thorsen House#Sigma Phi Society of the Thorsen House|Sigma Phi Society of the Thorsen House]] (alternatively '''Thorsen''' or the '''Sigma Phi Society of California'''), which hosts communal dinners, organizes small concerts, and offers tours for other students and members of the public, welcoming thousands of visitors a year.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/The-Ultimate-Bungalow-Dropping-by-Berkeley-s-2549461.php|title=The Ultimate Bungalow / Dropping by Berkeley's Thorsen House|last=Whiting|first=Sam|date=2003-11-09|website=SFGate|access-date=2019-07-02}}</ref>\n\nThorsen can be toured throughout the week on an informal basis; one can simply knock on the door to visit.<ref>[http://www.thorsenhouse.org/ Official Thorsen House Website] ''(Sigma Phi Society)''  access date: 1/4/2010</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[Image:Thorsen House Window.JPG|thumb|200px|left|Detail of Leaded Art Glass window in the Thorsen House.]]\n\n=== Namesake ===\nThe Thorsen House is named after William Randolph Thorsen (1860-1942), a lumber baron from [[Michigan]] who retired to and purchased a lot in [[Berkeley, California]]. His wife, Caroline Canfield Thorsen (1858-1942), was the younger sister of Nellie Canfield Blacker, owner of the [[Robert R. Blacker House]] in [[Pasadena, California]]. The couple resided in the house following its construction and until their deaths in 1942.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Design ===\nThe house embodies the [[American Craftsman|American Craftsman style]] of the [[Arts and Crafts Movement]], a style [[Greene and Greene|Greene & Greene]] is  known for incorporating in their projects (as is the case with [[Gamble House (Pasadena, California)|Gamble House]] and [[Robert R. Blacker House|Blacker House]], both in [[Pasadena, California|Pasadena]]).\n\nThe entry hall is paneled in [[Teak in Myanmar|Burmese Teak]] while the living and dining rooms are paneled in [[Honduras Mahogany]] with [[ebony]] pegs covering the screws. The fireplace in the living room is encased in mauve tile from the [[Grueby Faience Company]]. The front door contains leaded art glass in the pattern of a gnarled grape vine, executed by Emil Lange, who also worked on the [[Gamble House (Pasadena, California)|Gamble House]]. The Greenes were originally commissioned to make furniture for the dining room, but were later called back to make additional pieces.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Greene and Greene|Greene & Greene]]\n* [[Gamble House (Pasadena, California)|Gamble House]]\n* [[Robert R. Blacker House]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Related reading==\n*Bosley, Edward R.; Robert Judson Clark; Randell L. Makinson   (1996) ''Last of the Ultimate Bungalows. The William R. Thorsen House of Greene and Greene'' (University of California)\n*Makinson, Randall (2001) ''Greene & Greene: Architecture as a Fine Art'' (Gibbs Smith) {{ISBN|978-1586851057}}\n*Johnson, Robert; Janet Byron (2015) ''Berkeley Walks: Revealing Rambles through America's Most Intriguing City'' (Roaring Forties Press) {{ISBN|9781938901515}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.thorsenhouse.org/ Official Thorsen House Website]  (Sigma Phi Society - Tours) \n*[http://www.usc.edu/dept/architecture/greeneandgreene/259.html Greene and Greene Virtual Archives Website]\n*[http://www.berkeleyheritage.com/berkeley_landmarks/landmarks.html Berkeley Landmarks Website]\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places in California}}\n\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1909]]\n[[Category:Houses on the National Register of Historic Places in California]]\n[[Category:History of Alameda County, California]]\n[[Category:Arts and Crafts architecture in California]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Berkeley, California]]\n[[Category:Historic house museums in California]]\n[[Category:Bungalow architecture in California]]\n[[Category:American Craftsman architecture in California]]\n[[Category:Houses in Alameda County, California]]\n[[Category:Museums in Berkeley, California]]\n[[Category:Fraternity and sorority houses]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Berkeley, California]]\n[[Category:Sigma Phi]]\n[[Category:Greene and Greene buildings]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NRHP | name =William R. Thorsen House\n  | nrhp_type = \n  | image = Thorsen House.jpg\n  | caption = \n  | location= 2307 [[Piedmont Avenue (Berkeley)|Piedmont Ave]], [[Berkeley, California]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|37|52|8.34|N|122|15|7.09|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = United States Oakland#California#USA\n  | built =1909\n  | designated_other1 = Berkeley Landmark \n  | designated_other1_date = December 15, 1975 <ref name=\"Berkeley Landmarks\">{{cite web|url=http://berkeleyheritage.com/berkeley_landmarks/landmarks1-100.html|title=Berkeley Landmarks::Landmarks #1-100|date=2010-06-06|work=Berkeley Landmarks|publisher=Berkeley Architectural Heritage Association}}</ref>\n  | designated_other1_number = 4\n  | architect= [[Greene and Greene|Greene & Greene]]<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.californiasigmaphi.org/about/thorsenhouse/|title=   The Thorsen House  \n|publisher= California Sigma Phi Society |accessdate= April 20, 2016}}</ref>\n  | architecture= [[Ultimate bungalow]], [[American Craftsman|American Arts and Crafts Movement]]\n  | added = November 20, 1978<ref name=\"nris\" />\n  | area = {{convert|0.4|acre}}\n  | governing_body = <!--Local-->Private \n  | refnum = 78000646<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''William R. Thorsen House''', often referred to as the '''Thorsen House''', is a historic residence in [[Berkeley, California]]. Built in 1909 for William and Caroline Thorsen, it is one of the last of four standing [[ultimate bungalow]]s designed by Henry and Charles Greene of the renowned architectural firm [[Greene & Greene]] and the only one located in [[Northern California]].<ref